1
00:00:30,930 --> 00:00:33,632
♪

2
00:00:41,241 --> 00:00:47,046
( Spectators cheering )

3
00:01:32,158 --> 00:01:34,093
( Engine roaring )

4
00:01:42,235 --> 00:01:47,339
( Heartbeat )

5
00:01:47,341 --> 00:01:50,175
( Heartbeat slows )

6
00:01:50,177 --> 00:01:52,711
( Engines roaring )

7
00:03:01,314 --> 00:03:04,383
( Low, steady heartbeat )

8
00:03:25,939 --> 00:03:29,308
( Sirens approaching )

9
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:40,953
Martin brundle: Everybody
thought I was dead.

10
00:03:40,955 --> 00:03:43,322
I didn't have a bruise
on my body.

11
00:03:43,324 --> 00:03:45,757
I didn't have anything at all.

12
00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:49,661
I looked up,
and I saw a red flag.

13
00:03:49,663 --> 00:03:52,764
That's lucky--
they've stopped the race.

14
00:03:55,635 --> 00:03:58,136
Back then, we had
the restarts, and...

15
00:03:58,138 --> 00:03:59,805
Also we had spare cars,

16
00:03:59,807 --> 00:04:02,641
so your mind goes,
"get in the spare car."

17
00:04:02,643 --> 00:04:04,343
And new ear plugs!
Man: Yes, okay.

18
00:04:04,345 --> 00:04:06,578
And new gl--
and new gloves!

19
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:09,848
Martin brundle: And so, you can't start
until you've seen Professor Watkins.

20
00:04:09,850 --> 00:04:12,451
"Where's sid?
Anybody know where sid is?"

21
00:04:14,020 --> 00:04:16,255
I ran towards him like crazy.

22
00:04:22,795 --> 00:04:24,796
I got there, and he said,
"I can see you're okay.

23
00:04:24,798 --> 00:04:27,566
I've just watched you run
300 meters. What's the date?"

24
00:04:27,568 --> 00:04:29,134
I said, "it's the 10th
of march."

25
00:04:29,136 --> 00:04:31,536
He said, "yeah, then
you're fine. Get in the car."

26
00:04:31,538 --> 00:04:34,906
♪

27
00:04:44,384 --> 00:04:46,451
Martin brundle:
There is no doubt about it--

28
00:04:46,453 --> 00:04:48,687
a few years before,
I would have been a dead man.

29
00:04:51,858 --> 00:04:54,493
Martin brundle: We want
to see something exceptional,

30
00:04:54,495 --> 00:04:57,963
breathtaking, that we
think we can't do.

31
00:04:57,965 --> 00:05:00,766
We want to see gladiators,
warriors.

32
00:05:00,768 --> 00:05:03,969
And let's face it, we do like
to see a bit of a shunt.

33
00:05:05,705 --> 00:05:08,640
But we don't
want to see deaths.

34
00:05:08,642 --> 00:05:13,545
Man: Miracle of miracles!
This is well nigh unbelievable!

35
00:05:13,547 --> 00:05:16,214
Martin brundle
gets out of the car,

36
00:05:16,216 --> 00:05:18,784
and he's seemingly
all right.

37
00:05:18,786 --> 00:05:21,286
Martin brundle: It is
incredible how this changed,

38
00:05:21,288 --> 00:05:24,923
and how suddenly it became unacceptable
to die in the name of sport.

39
00:05:35,234 --> 00:05:37,936
♪

40
00:05:49,882 --> 00:05:52,517
Man: Grand prix is like
the Olympics of motor sports,

41
00:05:52,519 --> 00:05:54,586
with the cars in
all national colors:

42
00:05:54,588 --> 00:05:56,755
Blue for the French,
green for the British,

43
00:05:56,757 --> 00:05:59,057
red for Italy,
and white for the Germans,

44
00:05:59,059 --> 00:06:02,494
until Mercedes stopped using
paint on those silver arrows...

45
00:06:06,099 --> 00:06:07,733
Man: Michael schumacher wins,

46
00:06:07,735 --> 00:06:13,305
and becomes the most successful
grand prix driver of all time!

47
00:06:13,307 --> 00:06:17,008
Man: ...The silver cars that
are the pride of Hitler Germany.

48
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:23,515
Man: Alfa Romeo wins,
driven by the fabulous nouvalri.

49
00:06:25,918 --> 00:06:28,787
Man: What a feeling
for Fernando Alonzo.

50
00:06:28,789 --> 00:06:32,124
He wins the Italian
grand prix at monza.

51
00:06:34,894 --> 00:06:37,629
Man: As the French announce
their search for the fastest man

52
00:06:37,631 --> 00:06:41,633
in a new world championship
series to be entitled formula 1,

53
00:06:41,635 --> 00:06:45,036
with the inaugural race
to be held at silverstone.

54
00:06:50,543 --> 00:06:52,644
Man: Enzo Ferrari for one
is not impressed

55
00:06:52,646 --> 00:06:54,946
with the new wave
of British motor racers.

56
00:06:54,948 --> 00:06:57,949
<i>Il commendatore</i> has labeled
the new independent designers

57
00:06:57,951 --> 00:07:01,753
<i>garagistes,</i> the men
who cannot build engines.

58
00:07:04,390 --> 00:07:06,124
Man: Fangio is beaten
in buenos aires

59
00:07:06,126 --> 00:07:09,327
by former teammate
and fastest rival stirling moss,

60
00:07:09,329 --> 00:07:12,531
in a Cooper funny car,
no less.

61
00:07:12,533 --> 00:07:14,966
Man: What courage
by these men,

62
00:07:14,968 --> 00:07:16,968
to push these cars
and themselves

63
00:07:16,970 --> 00:07:21,506
to their very limits.
But that is formula 1.

64
00:07:57,009 --> 00:08:00,212
Narrator: <i>Formula 1</i>
<i>was born in a bygone time...</i>

65
00:08:02,815 --> 00:08:07,018
<i>When boys' heroes</i>
<i>reigned in the sky.</i>

66
00:08:13,226 --> 00:08:15,727
Nigel mansell: When you're young, 
you wanted to be a formula 1 driver.

67
00:08:15,729 --> 00:08:17,395
You wanted to be an astronaut,

68
00:08:17,397 --> 00:08:20,632
you wanted to be
a fighter pilot.

69
00:08:20,634 --> 00:08:22,400
Damon hill:
After the second world war,

70
00:08:22,402 --> 00:08:23,935
the mindset of going off

71
00:08:23,937 --> 00:08:27,439
and doing something
courageous in a vehicle,

72
00:08:27,441 --> 00:08:31,843
this just naturally flowed
into what became formula 1.

73
00:08:50,296 --> 00:08:53,932
Martin brundle: When you see photographs
and film of that era,

74
00:08:53,934 --> 00:08:56,735
the seriousness of them
is awe inspiring.

75
00:08:58,271 --> 00:09:00,272
I grew up in that world.

76
00:09:00,274 --> 00:09:04,776
My dad was world champion '62,
and I was 2.

77
00:09:04,778 --> 00:09:07,779
They all had this
genuineness about them.

78
00:09:07,781 --> 00:09:10,582
They all
were the real article.

79
00:09:14,887 --> 00:09:18,089
John Watson: I certainly had respect
to those that went before me.

80
00:09:18,091 --> 00:09:19,791
Some of them
were my contemporaries.

81
00:09:19,793 --> 00:09:22,427
I met one time probably
in my view

82
00:09:22,429 --> 00:09:25,163
the greatest
grand prix driver ever,

83
00:09:25,165 --> 00:09:28,767
and that includes people
like Michael schumacher and ayrton senna.

84
00:09:31,370 --> 00:09:32,904
Fangio.
Fangio.

85
00:09:32,906 --> 00:09:34,205
Fangio.
Fangio.

86
00:09:34,207 --> 00:09:35,340
Fangio.

87
00:09:35,342 --> 00:09:36,875
Juan Manuel fangio.

88
00:09:43,149 --> 00:09:45,784
Narrator: <i>The first big name</i>
<i>in formula one</i>

89
00:09:45,786 --> 00:09:47,786
<i>may have been</i>
<i>the best driver ever.</i>

90
00:09:47,788 --> 00:09:50,288
<i>Fangio would win</i>
<i>five world titles,</i>

91
00:09:50,290 --> 00:09:53,491
<i>a record that stood</i>
<i>for 40 years,</i>

92
00:09:53,493 --> 00:09:56,328
<i>surpassed only</i>
<i>by Michael schumacher.</i>

93
00:09:58,130 --> 00:10:01,733
Whenever you drive those cars
that fangio had to race in,

94
00:10:01,735 --> 00:10:03,802
it's very scary.

95
00:10:03,804 --> 00:10:07,105
You have to hold yourself
on the steering wheel.

96
00:10:07,107 --> 00:10:08,340
No safety belts.

97
00:10:08,342 --> 00:10:11,009
The helmet was
just like a hat.

98
00:10:11,011 --> 00:10:15,513
Goggles. And you
had to be brave.

99
00:10:15,515 --> 00:10:18,550
Narrator: <i>The most celebrated</i>
<i>driver in a dangerous time</i>

100
00:10:18,552 --> 00:10:20,485
<i>survived.</i>

101
00:10:20,487 --> 00:10:25,724
<i>The year fangio retired,</i>
<i>1958, the formula changed.</i>

102
00:10:28,160 --> 00:10:30,662
<i>The sport's governing body</i>
<i>announced from Paris</i>

103
00:10:30,664 --> 00:10:35,867
<i>that formula one would crown</i>
<i>two world champions each season--</i>

104
00:10:35,869 --> 00:10:38,336
<i>one title for</i>
<i>the fastest driver,</i>

105
00:10:38,338 --> 00:10:42,073
<i>and another for the manufacturer</i>
<i>of the fastest machine.</i>

106
00:10:46,979 --> 00:10:49,447
Mario andretti: This was
the evolution, you know?

107
00:10:49,449 --> 00:10:52,350
Each team
has to take engines,

108
00:10:52,352 --> 00:10:56,921
take chassis and technology
to the absolute limit.

109
00:10:56,923 --> 00:10:59,024
Narrator: <i>In this</i>
<i>new competition,</i>

110
00:10:59,026 --> 00:11:04,162
<i>the British began to challenge</i>
<i> the old world continental powers.</i>

111
00:11:04,164 --> 00:11:06,364
John barnard: All the English
teams were considered to be

112
00:11:06,366 --> 00:11:12,303
the <i>garagist</i>by... by Ferrari
and the other racing teams.

113
00:11:12,305 --> 00:11:15,073
<i>One englishman would set</i>
<i>the pace of progress,</i>

114
00:11:15,075 --> 00:11:18,610
<i>in racing and the entire</i>
<i>automotive world.</i>

115
00:11:18,612 --> 00:11:21,146
Colin Chapman: We basically
go racing 'cause I like it.

116
00:11:22,815 --> 00:11:24,783
I like the competitiveness
of it,

117
00:11:24,785 --> 00:11:26,384
I like the comradeship of it.

118
00:11:26,386 --> 00:11:29,621
And I also like the technical
fallout that comes from it.

119
00:11:29,623 --> 00:11:32,057
John surtees: Colin Chapman
was a great character,

120
00:11:32,059 --> 00:11:34,459
if at times a bit cavalier.

121
00:11:34,461 --> 00:11:36,995
(Laughing softly)
Oh, I don't know about that.

122
00:11:36,997 --> 00:11:40,699
<i>Colin Chapman was</i>
<i>an engineer who learned to fly,</i>

123
00:11:40,701 --> 00:11:44,102
<i>an entrepreneur who made</i>
<i> lightweight sports cars for the public,</i>

124
00:11:44,104 --> 00:11:48,707
<i>as well as for grand prix,</i>
<i>under the name lotus.</i>

125
00:11:52,244 --> 00:11:54,979
In those days, lotus was
an out-and-out racing car.

126
00:11:56,882 --> 00:11:59,317
My father, he was
always pushing the envelope.

127
00:11:59,319 --> 00:12:02,487
Good engineering means you've
designed something to its limit.

128
00:12:04,023 --> 00:12:06,391
Colin was the Maverick
of all time.

129
00:12:06,393 --> 00:12:07,926
He was a genius.

130
00:12:07,928 --> 00:12:11,763
He was <i>the</i> team owner
that you want to drive for.

131
00:12:15,167 --> 00:12:17,435
<i>By 1963,</i>
<i>Chapman had designed</i>

132
00:12:17,437 --> 00:12:20,772
<i>the fastest machine</i>
<i>in formula one...</i>

133
00:12:20,774 --> 00:12:24,075
<i>And he had the fastest man</i>
<i>behind the wheel of a lotus.</i>

134
00:12:34,053 --> 00:12:36,321
Sir Jackie Stewart: Jim Clark
was the best racing driver

135
00:12:36,323 --> 00:12:38,123
I ever raced against.

136
00:12:39,358 --> 00:12:43,428
The whole exercise was to be
as good as you can get--

137
00:12:43,430 --> 00:12:45,430
on the limit.

138
00:12:45,432 --> 00:12:46,965
And Jimmy
drove in such a way

139
00:12:46,967 --> 00:12:48,433
that he was never
over the limit.

140
00:12:48,435 --> 00:12:51,302
He was never erratic.
He was never spectacular.

141
00:12:51,304 --> 00:12:56,374
He was spectacularly fast,
but in an unspectacular fashion.

142
00:12:56,376 --> 00:13:00,712
It was smooth and clean
and beautifully handled.

143
00:13:00,714 --> 00:13:03,615
<i>He would win more formula one</i>
<i>championship races</i>

144
00:13:03,617 --> 00:13:05,483
<i>than any driver before him,</i>

145
00:13:05,485 --> 00:13:09,788
<i>finishing in second place</i>
<i>only once in his career.</i>

146
00:13:09,790 --> 00:13:11,322
Sir Jackie Stewart:
He was a country boy.

147
00:13:11,324 --> 00:13:14,726
He was a farmer from
the borders of Scotland,

148
00:13:14,728 --> 00:13:17,529
quiet and almost innocent.

149
00:13:17,531 --> 00:13:20,064
Jim Clark: I'd like to get
back here much more often.

150
00:13:20,066 --> 00:13:22,867
It's, uh, great relaxation
to get back here,

151
00:13:22,869 --> 00:13:27,372
and very much
the opposite from racing.

152
00:13:32,111 --> 00:13:34,345
<i>Clark became the face</i>
<i>of formula one,</i>

153
00:13:34,347 --> 00:13:36,548
<i>with another champion,</i>
<i>Graham hill,</i>

154
00:13:36,550 --> 00:13:38,950
<i>playing his affable foil.</i>

155
00:13:38,952 --> 00:13:40,251
Damon hill: Everyone
was quite close.

156
00:13:40,253 --> 00:13:42,520
Jim Clark
had been to our house,

157
00:13:42,522 --> 00:13:46,224
and I knew Colin Chapman
sort of the same way as I knew my dad.

158
00:13:46,226 --> 00:13:48,960
They sounded the same,
and they had the same mustache.

159
00:13:48,962 --> 00:13:50,762
Sally swart: Colin
was an extreme extrovert,

160
00:13:50,764 --> 00:13:52,497
great fun to be with,

161
00:13:52,499 --> 00:13:56,067
but very different
in character to Jimmy, really.

162
00:13:56,069 --> 00:13:59,938
Jimmy was quieter.
But they were like brothers.

163
00:14:01,640 --> 00:14:03,241
<i>Together, they were</i>
<i>racing on the limit</i>

164
00:14:03,243 --> 00:14:07,579
<i>of manmade speed</i>
<i>and ingenuity.</i>

165
00:14:07,581 --> 00:14:09,914
<i>They won four world</i>
<i>championships between them,</i>

166
00:14:09,916 --> 00:14:13,051
<i>and a record five</i>
<i>British grand prix.</i>

167
00:14:14,153 --> 00:14:16,421
<i>But for all their success,</i>

168
00:14:16,423 --> 00:14:18,423
<i>they failed to take</i>
<i>the checkered flag</i>

169
00:14:18,425 --> 00:14:20,959
<i>at the most famous</i>
<i>motor race of all.</i>

170
00:14:46,185 --> 00:14:49,454
<i>Fast cars and courageous souls</i>
<i>from all over the world</i>

171
00:14:49,456 --> 00:14:53,658
<i>have been racing through</i>
<i>these streets since 1929.</i>

172
00:14:57,663 --> 00:15:00,164
Monaco is terrifying.

173
00:15:00,166 --> 00:15:01,966
You cannot believe
it's possible

174
00:15:01,968 --> 00:15:04,435
to hold a motor race
round Monaco.

175
00:15:04,437 --> 00:15:07,572
In the first few laps, you stick your head up
to see where it went, 'cause

176
00:15:07,574 --> 00:15:11,042
it's just guardrails
that you can't hardly see.

177
00:15:11,044 --> 00:15:13,177
You're millimeters
away from barriers.

178
00:15:22,655 --> 00:15:24,889
Jenson button: 
You either do a lap that you're so proud of--

179
00:15:24,891 --> 00:15:28,126
you're always wondering
if you're ever gonna do that again--

180
00:15:28,128 --> 00:15:30,828
or you end up in the wall.

181
00:15:30,830 --> 00:15:32,430
Lewis Hamilton:
The danger aspect to this

182
00:15:32,432 --> 00:15:34,899
is one of the parts
that drives us racing drivers.

183
00:15:34,901 --> 00:15:36,367
It's something we love.

184
00:15:40,339 --> 00:15:42,573
<i>One man</i>
<i>mastered these streets</i>

185
00:15:42,575 --> 00:15:45,276
<i>like no other driver</i>
<i>in history.</i>

186
00:15:45,278 --> 00:15:47,845
Jo Ramirez: Monaco was
a special place for senna.

187
00:15:47,847 --> 00:15:50,014
He was the best in the world.

188
00:15:50,016 --> 00:15:55,386
His concentration on
one lap was just uncanny.

189
00:15:55,388 --> 00:16:00,091
♪

190
00:17:11,563 --> 00:17:14,832
Narrator: <i>Ayrton senna</i>
<i>won Monaco a record six times,</i>

191
00:17:14,834 --> 00:17:18,636
<i>one more victory than the man</i>
<i>with the derring-do mustache.</i>

192
00:17:23,175 --> 00:17:26,177
<i>Graham hill came</i>
<i>to Monaco in 1966</i>

193
00:17:26,179 --> 00:17:28,846
<i>to defend his</i>
<i>third straight victory.</i>

194
00:17:28,848 --> 00:17:31,349
Graham hill: It's a tremendous race 
and a great one to come and watch,

195
00:17:31,351 --> 00:17:34,385
and if anybody's gonna come and see 
a grand prix, this is really the one.

196
00:17:34,387 --> 00:17:36,454
It's such a nice place
to be, anyway.

197
00:17:43,962 --> 00:17:45,830
To come to Monaco
and talk to <i>men</i>

198
00:17:45,832 --> 00:17:47,765
is a waste of time,
so excuse me.

199
00:17:47,767 --> 00:17:52,236
That's when motor racing
was really dangerous,

200
00:17:52,238 --> 00:17:53,638
and sex was safe.

201
00:17:53,640 --> 00:17:56,674
Mario andretti: Still today,
what defines formula one

202
00:17:56,676 --> 00:17:59,277
is the sense of prestige.

203
00:17:59,279 --> 00:18:03,114
It's an event.
Kings want to be there.

204
00:18:06,618 --> 00:18:10,421
Princess grace of Monaco: For me,
it's a thrill to see an expert at work.

205
00:18:10,423 --> 00:18:13,324
Upon meeting Graham hill,
you like him.

206
00:18:13,326 --> 00:18:16,360
Watching him made me become
more interested in racing

207
00:18:16,362 --> 00:18:18,463
and what these men were doing.

208
00:18:18,465 --> 00:18:21,499
<i>In those days,</i>
<i>hill's fiercest rivals</i>

209
00:18:21,501 --> 00:18:24,368
<i>were also</i>
<i>his closest friends.</i>

210
00:18:28,340 --> 00:18:31,742
( Indistinct remarks
and laughter )

211
00:18:31,744 --> 00:18:34,212
Sir Jackie Stewart:
The intimacy was incredible,

212
00:18:34,214 --> 00:18:36,948
from the racing drivers
to the mechanics

213
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:38,483
to the wives
and the girlfriends.

214
00:18:38,485 --> 00:18:40,651
The camaraderie
was very deep.

215
00:18:45,257 --> 00:18:47,091
Sir Jackie Stewart:
We went on holidays together.

216
00:18:47,093 --> 00:18:49,827
We lived together.
We traveled together.

217
00:18:49,829 --> 00:18:53,030
Brigitte hill: You felt
very much part of this family

218
00:18:53,032 --> 00:18:54,999
growing up together.

219
00:18:55,001 --> 00:18:57,201
Motor racing
was just a part of it.

220
00:18:57,203 --> 00:18:59,370
<i>The drivers</i>
<i>formed a trade union,</i>

221
00:18:59,372 --> 00:19:02,373
<i>the grand prix drivers'</i>
<i>association.</i>

222
00:19:04,409 --> 00:19:07,678
<i>The women soon followed suit</i>
<i>with the doghouse club.</i>

223
00:19:09,448 --> 00:19:11,415
Damon hill: Well,
the doghouse club

224
00:19:11,417 --> 00:19:14,685
is where <i>i</i> was kept growing up with
the wives and girlfriends of drivers.

