01:24:55,524 --> 01:24:58,025
That's exactly
what he wants to do,

1361
01:24:58,027 --> 01:24:59,827
get in front
of all those cars,

1362
01:24:59,829 --> 01:25:02,963
because when you're in the front,
you don't have that spray.

1363
01:25:02,965 --> 01:25:06,800
When you're stuck behind in second, third,
fourth, or wherever,

1364
01:25:06,802 --> 01:25:09,503
you have this massive plume
of spray in your face.

1365
01:25:09,505 --> 01:25:12,172
It's impossible
to see anything.

1366
01:25:12,174 --> 01:25:15,843
James hunt in the lead,
in the Marlboro mclaren.

1367
01:25:15,845 --> 01:25:17,811
This is the start he needs.

1368
01:25:19,481 --> 01:25:21,014
Mario andretti:
The visibility,

1369
01:25:21,016 --> 01:25:22,850
especially at
the beginning of the race,

1370
01:25:22,852 --> 01:25:25,285
was no more
than 20%, at best.

1371
01:25:25,287 --> 01:25:26,787
Man: Look at that mist!

1372
01:25:26,789 --> 01:25:30,357
How can they see anything
driving in these conditions?

1373
01:25:30,359 --> 01:25:32,226
A hundred and eighty
Miles an hour,

1374
01:25:32,228 --> 01:25:35,496
you're listening, and then you're watching
your side of the road,

1375
01:25:35,498 --> 01:25:37,397
and if the car
in front of you stops,

1376
01:25:37,399 --> 01:25:39,066
you're gonna be
in trouble.

1377
01:25:39,068 --> 01:25:41,168
Man: And there's Jody scheckter,
going down on the inside.

1378
01:25:41,170 --> 01:25:44,171
Perhaps he thinks there's better grip
down there on the inside.

1379
01:25:44,173 --> 01:25:46,206
And there, lauda,
in the pits already,

1380
01:25:46,208 --> 01:25:49,042
having a cockpit conference
with forghieri,

1381
01:25:49,044 --> 01:25:52,312
the leader of
the Ferrari team.

1382
01:25:52,314 --> 01:25:54,348
What's happened to lauda?

1383
01:25:56,151 --> 01:25:57,384
Niki decided to stop.

1384
01:25:57,386 --> 01:26:00,187
Man: And there is
James hunt for the lead,

1385
01:26:00,189 --> 01:26:03,857
and lauda seemingly
out of the race already.

1386
01:26:03,859 --> 01:26:05,926
He stopped. That was it.

1387
01:26:05,928 --> 01:26:08,462
In the entire 40-odd years
I've been involved,

1388
01:26:08,464 --> 01:26:10,164
that's the only time
I can remember

1389
01:26:10,166 --> 01:26:14,201
a driver actually stopping
because the conditions were so dangerous.

1390
01:26:14,203 --> 01:26:15,369
Just incredible.

1391
01:26:15,371 --> 01:26:16,837
Man: He's spinning!

1392
01:26:16,839 --> 01:26:19,306
( Indistinct remark )
...Out of the race completely,

1393
01:26:19,308 --> 01:26:23,544
and out of
the world championship!

1394
01:26:23,546 --> 01:26:25,712
Jody scheckter:
It takes big balls

1395
01:26:25,714 --> 01:26:28,682
to make
a decision like that.

1396
01:26:28,684 --> 01:26:30,584
Some people may think
it's cowardly.

1397
01:26:30,586 --> 01:26:33,587
Um, I think it's
probably the opposite.

1398
01:26:36,057 --> 01:26:38,425
He went against
all the things that

1399
01:26:38,427 --> 01:26:41,061
being a grand prix driver
at Ferrari are about--

1400
01:26:41,063 --> 01:26:43,430
in other words,
you drive for Ferrari, not yourself,

1401
01:26:43,432 --> 01:26:46,266
and if you've got
to die doing it, so be it.

1402
01:26:46,268 --> 01:26:49,269
Die, but at least
die trying.

1403
01:26:50,905 --> 01:26:53,907
Ferrari were actually
embarrassed for him.

1404
01:26:53,909 --> 01:26:57,110
You know... "No, the car is--
the engine is finished..."

1405
01:26:57,112 --> 01:26:58,612
And all the rest of it.

1406
01:26:58,614 --> 01:27:01,148
Lauda actually got angry
when he heard them doing that,

1407
01:27:01,150 --> 01:27:02,816
and told it straight.

1408
01:27:02,818 --> 01:27:06,954
Koen vergeer: He was the one who resisted
the myth of Ferrari,

1409
01:27:06,956 --> 01:27:08,422
and he said no, no.

1410
01:27:08,424 --> 01:27:11,225
Who said that before
to enzo Ferrari?

1411
01:27:13,461 --> 01:27:17,831
To these days, I think I would 
never forgive Niki lauda.

1412
01:27:17,833 --> 01:27:19,600
That particular moment,

1413
01:27:19,602 --> 01:27:21,768
he thought it was
too dangerous for him,

1414
01:27:21,770 --> 01:27:26,139
and he forget the...
50, 60 people from Ferrari

1415
01:27:26,141 --> 01:27:27,608
helping him to achieve.

1416
01:27:28,776 --> 01:27:32,679
The thousands of people
in the whole of Italy--

1417
01:27:33,781 --> 01:27:36,450
he forgot all of
those people in that time,

1418
01:27:36,452 --> 01:27:39,486
and their beloved lauda,
he become selfish

1419
01:27:39,488 --> 01:27:41,855
and he said,
"no, I don't want to drive."

1420
01:27:43,791 --> 01:27:45,692
Niki lauda:
I don't regret it.

1421
01:27:48,062 --> 01:27:50,764
But I already saw
what can happen.

1422
01:27:52,967 --> 01:27:55,669
Man: And so we've got
about four laps to go,

1423
01:27:55,671 --> 01:27:57,838
and James hunt
is still second.

1424
01:27:57,840 --> 01:28:00,040
Maurice Hamilton: The championship 
wasn't settled there and then

1425
01:28:00,042 --> 01:28:01,341
when he stepped
out of the car

1426
01:28:01,343 --> 01:28:03,710
because James had
to finish third or higher.

1427
01:28:03,712 --> 01:28:07,848
Man: James hunt's in the pits
with one bald tire

1428
01:28:07,850 --> 01:28:12,185
and the others flat.

1429
01:28:12,187 --> 01:28:15,822
But there is Mario andretti,
in the lead.

1430
01:28:15,824 --> 01:28:19,293
Now, where does that leave
hunt as he exits the pits?

1431
01:28:19,295 --> 01:28:23,263
Is hunt still
in the top two hunt?

1432
01:28:23,265 --> 01:28:27,067
James hunt,
racing for his life.

1433
01:28:27,069 --> 01:28:33,840
I think hunt
is currently fourth.

1434
01:28:33,842 --> 01:28:36,543
And there's hunt,
going past Alan Jones.

1435
01:28:36,545 --> 01:28:38,378
That will put him
into third place,

1436
01:28:38,380 --> 01:28:41,515
and into the world
champion title!

1437
01:28:41,517 --> 01:28:43,216
Will his car
hold together?

1438
01:28:43,218 --> 01:28:44,551
James hunt...

1439
01:28:44,553 --> 01:28:47,254
And Mario andretti
takes the flag,

1440
01:28:47,256 --> 01:28:49,022
and here comes hunt!

1441
01:28:49,024 --> 01:28:54,161
James hunt has done it!
Hunt is the champion!

1442
01:28:54,163 --> 01:28:59,499
♪

1443
01:29:05,373 --> 01:29:07,040
When he got out of the car,

1444
01:29:07,042 --> 01:29:09,276
James didn't know if
he'd won the championship.

1445
01:29:09,278 --> 01:29:11,445
He thought
he'd finished fourth.

1446
01:29:11,447 --> 01:29:15,115
( Vintage audio )

1447
01:29:18,986 --> 01:29:22,856
Hunt was world champion
in the end, by one point.

1448
01:29:22,858 --> 01:29:26,493
Dramatic formula one folklore.
It'll be there forever.

1449
01:29:28,129 --> 01:29:30,430
I met Niki. The first thing
he said to me was,

1450
01:29:30,432 --> 01:29:33,600
"I loved your father."

1451
01:29:33,602 --> 01:29:35,769
And, I mean, I think dad
quit at the end of the season.

1452
01:29:35,771 --> 01:29:39,373
He wished he could have shared
the championship with Niki.

1453
01:29:39,375 --> 01:29:40,607
They both lived to win,

1454
01:29:40,609 --> 01:29:41,708
and he wanted
to share it with him.

1455
01:29:41,710 --> 01:29:43,410
But he couldn't,
obviously.

1456
01:29:45,246 --> 01:29:47,848
<i>There can be only... one.</i>

1457
01:29:51,953 --> 01:29:55,188
That was his shooting star
moment, I think,

1458
01:29:55,190 --> 01:30:00,494
and it was the seminal
changing point in formula one.

1459
01:30:01,929 --> 01:30:05,866
<i>The fairytale ending</i>
<i>belonged to hunt,</i>

1460
01:30:05,868 --> 01:30:07,834
<i>but it was lauda's decision</i>

1461
01:30:07,836 --> 01:30:09,636
<i>to quit with the championship</i>
<i>on the line</i>

1462
01:30:09,638 --> 01:30:12,672
<i>that helped change</i>
<i>the sport forever.</i>

1463
01:30:14,475 --> 01:30:16,543
<i>If the fastest drivers</i>
<i>refuse to race</i>

1464
01:30:16,545 --> 01:30:18,478
<i>out of fear for their lives</i>

1465
01:30:18,480 --> 01:30:21,214
<i>with the entire</i>
<i>world watching,</i>

1466
01:30:21,216 --> 01:30:22,816
<i>there is no formula one.</i>

1467
01:30:22,818 --> 01:30:26,820
We understood that
culling racing drivers is not a good deal.

1468
01:30:26,822 --> 01:30:29,556
The public doesn't want
to see these heroes

1469
01:30:29,558 --> 01:30:32,492
dying on television,
dying in your living room.

1470
01:30:32,494 --> 01:30:35,829
Man: This week's big event
is the British grand prix.

1471
01:30:35,831 --> 01:30:38,832
Really, safety
came about with money.

1472
01:30:38,834 --> 01:30:41,368
John hogan: And that was all to do 
with the television.

1473
01:30:41,370 --> 01:30:42,636
That was
the real breakthrough.

1474
01:30:42,638 --> 01:30:45,071
That's not really true.

1475
01:30:45,073 --> 01:30:47,107
The money helped,

1476
01:30:47,109 --> 01:30:49,042
but the whole point
about safety is it depends

1477
01:30:49,044 --> 01:30:51,578
on the attitude of the people
running the sport.

1478
01:30:51,580 --> 01:30:54,347
<i>The new men taking</i>
<i>the lead in the fight</i>

1479
01:30:54,349 --> 01:30:57,317
<i>were survivors</i>
<i>in their own right.</i>

1480
01:30:57,319 --> 01:31:00,620
It was obvious that something
needed to be done.

1481
01:31:00,622 --> 01:31:04,991
<i>A decade after Jim Clark's death</i>
<i>shocked the world,</i>

1482
01:31:04,993 --> 01:31:06,893
<i>Bernie ecclestone</i>
<i>quietly hired</i>

1483
01:31:06,895 --> 01:31:09,029
<i>the leading neurosurgeon</i>
<i>in London</i>

1484
01:31:09,031 --> 01:31:11,932
<i>as the official</i>
<i>race doctor for formula one.</i>

1485
01:31:13,434 --> 01:31:14,868
This was Bernie's idea,

1486
01:31:14,870 --> 01:31:16,770
to take on
this permanent doctor,

1487
01:31:16,772 --> 01:31:21,374
Professor sid Watkins,
a renowned brain surgeon.

1488
01:31:21,376 --> 01:31:24,077
Dr. sid Watkins:
The first year with Bernie

1489
01:31:24,079 --> 01:31:25,579
was a very difficult year

1490
01:31:25,581 --> 01:31:29,449
because nobody wanted
sid Watkins at the circuit.

1491
01:31:29,451 --> 01:31:31,218
Jody scheckter:
They've got their own doctors,

1492
01:31:31,220 --> 01:31:33,220
and they don't like
some englishman coming along

1493
01:31:33,222 --> 01:31:36,523
and saying, you know,
"we want to do this."

1494
01:31:36,525 --> 01:31:38,625
<i>At the German grand prix</i>
<i>in 1978--</i>

1495
01:31:38,627 --> 01:31:41,061
<i>Dr. Watkins' fourth race--</i>

1496
01:31:41,063 --> 01:31:43,263
<i>the organizers banned</i>
<i>the track doctor</i>

1497
01:31:43,265 --> 01:31:47,400
<i>from race control</i>
<i>just moments before the start.</i>

1498
01:31:47,402 --> 01:31:50,103
Bernie says,
"well, pack the cars. We're leaving."

1499
01:31:50,105 --> 01:31:52,739
Race control replied,
"what am I gonna do

1500
01:31:52,741 --> 01:31:55,809
with 80,000 Germans
who are here?"

1501
01:31:55,811 --> 01:31:58,645
And Bernie said,
"you can go and tell them to fuck themselves."

1502
01:32:00,948 --> 01:32:03,316
And they said, "the doctor
can come back in "

1503
01:32:03,318 --> 01:32:06,920
♪

1504
01:32:06,922 --> 01:32:08,722
It was always said
that sid Watkins

1505
01:32:08,724 --> 01:32:12,158
was the only man
to whom Bernie ecclestone always deferred.

1506
01:32:14,395 --> 01:32:18,431
<i>Four races later,</i>
<i>Dr. Watkins learned firsthand</i>

1507
01:32:18,433 --> 01:32:20,700
<i>the hardest lesson</i>
<i>in formula one.</i>

1508
01:32:21,636 --> 01:32:24,170
( Announcer speaking German )

1509
01:32:28,409 --> 01:32:30,810
( Spectators reacting )

1510
01:32:44,091 --> 01:32:47,394
Jane birbeck:
We watched it on TV.

1511
01:32:47,396 --> 01:32:50,063
James pulled Ronnie
out of the car.

1512
01:32:52,800 --> 01:32:55,302
I was prevented from
getting there by the police,

1513
01:32:55,304 --> 01:32:56,970
for about 20 minutes or so.

1514
01:32:56,972 --> 01:32:58,838
I mean,
it was absolute mayhem.

1515
01:33:03,277 --> 01:33:05,245
<i>The super Swede,</i>
<i>Ronnie Peterson,</i>

1516
01:33:05,247 --> 01:33:08,648
<i>had both of his legs</i>
<i>crushed in the pileup.</i>

1517
01:33:11,986 --> 01:33:16,222
Eventually, Ronnie
went off in the helicopter,

1518
01:33:16,224 --> 01:33:19,626
and we resumed the start.

1519
01:33:22,263 --> 01:33:24,297
<i>Colin Chapman won</i>
<i>his seventh and final</i>

1520
01:33:24,299 --> 01:33:26,967
<i>world championship</i>
<i>with Mario andretti.</i>

1521
01:33:28,002 --> 01:33:31,638
<i>He also lost his fifth driver.</i>

1522
01:33:31,640 --> 01:33:35,342
<i>Peterson died the next day,</i>
<i>after suffering an embolism.</i>

1523
01:33:37,578 --> 01:33:40,614
That was just
a sword through my heart.

1524
01:33:40,616 --> 01:33:44,017
He should not have died
from that.

1525
01:33:44,019 --> 01:33:47,387
If Dr. Watkins
was in charge at monza,

1526
01:33:47,389 --> 01:33:50,857
Ronnie Peterson would probably [Be]
sitting next to me.

1527
01:33:52,827 --> 01:33:55,862
Koen vergeer:
Peterson was one of the guys on my first race.

1528
01:33:55,864 --> 01:33:58,164
All the others disappeared.

1529
01:33:58,166 --> 01:34:01,334
They had stopped,
or they had died.

1530
01:34:01,336 --> 01:34:04,337
On that day,
when Ronnie Peterson died,

1531
01:34:04,339 --> 01:34:08,341
my childhood approach
to formula one ended.

1532
01:34:08,343 --> 01:34:11,111
It was a turning point
for the sport, too.

1533
01:34:15,750 --> 01:34:18,184
<i>From that race on,</i>
<i>Dr. Watkins began riding</i>

1534
01:34:18,186 --> 01:34:20,186
<i>in a safety</i>
<i>car behind every start,</i>

1535
01:34:20,188 --> 01:34:23,356
<i>for the most dangerous lap</i>
<i>of every race,</i>

1536
01:34:23,358 --> 01:34:27,527
<i>so he could be on hand</i>
<i>in the event of an accident.</i>

1537
01:34:27,529 --> 01:34:32,132
My job was really to look after the drivers,
and that's what I did.

1538
01:34:32,134 --> 01:34:34,901
<i>He standardized medical response</i>
<i>within formula one,</i>

1539
01:34:34,903 --> 01:34:38,905
<i>mandating permanent medical facilities</i>
<i>at each circuit</i>

1540
01:34:38,907 --> 01:34:42,275
<i>and helicopters on hand</i>
<i>for every race and practice.</i>

1541
01:34:42,277 --> 01:34:44,944
Sid Watkins was the man.

1542
01:34:48,916 --> 01:34:53,520
<i>Formula one still lost</i>
<i>four men in four years.</i>

1543
01:34:53,522 --> 01:34:55,588
Man: An outstanding
driver lost his life

1544
01:34:55,590 --> 01:34:57,424
through what was,
in my opinion,

1545
01:34:57,426 --> 01:35:00,760
a pure motor
racing accident.

1546
01:35:00,762 --> 01:35:02,595
<i>But only two drivers</i>
<i>were killed</i>

1547
01:35:02,597 --> 01:35:05,398
<i>over the next 12 years.</i>

1548
01:35:05,400 --> 01:35:08,768
<i>Each death was met with</i>
<i>scrutiny by the men in charge,</i>

1549
01:35:08,770 --> 01:35:11,104
<i>and a haunting refrain</i>
<i>by those</i>

1550
01:35:11,106 --> 01:35:13,840
<i>who knew too well</i>
<i>the price of glory.</i>

1551
01:35:15,076 --> 01:35:16,776
It's terribly, terribly sad,

1552
01:35:16,778 --> 01:35:18,812
but it's always happened
and it always will.

1553
01:35:18,814 --> 01:35:21,448
It's just intrinsic
to formula one.

1554
01:35:24,719 --> 01:35:26,386
<i>Until one.</i>

1555
01:35:29,256 --> 01:35:31,257
Martin brundle:
I was driving in the race,

1556
01:35:31,259 --> 01:35:33,259
and it was
a really strange time.

1557
01:35:33,261 --> 01:35:36,863
We had just lost roland ratzenberger
a day earlier.

1558
01:35:36,865 --> 01:35:38,832
And everybody starts
looking over their shoulder

1559
01:35:38,834 --> 01:35:41,034
and looking round at
what's gonna happen next.

1560
01:35:49,977 --> 01:35:52,479
And I remember that evening
that we were talking about,

1561
01:35:52,481 --> 01:35:53,813
yep, it was ratzenberger.

1562
01:35:53,815 --> 01:35:56,683
It was, like, his first race.

1563
01:35:56,685 --> 01:36:01,187
Not for one minute
I thought it could ever happen to senna.

1564
01:36:02,823 --> 01:36:04,157
<i>The three-time world champion</i>

1565
01:36:04,159 --> 01:36:06,793
<i>had become the new face</i>
<i>of formula one,</i>

1566
01:36:06,795 --> 01:36:11,998
<i>the one driver who could</i>
<i>finally challenge the great fangio.</i>

1567
01:36:12,000 --> 01:36:14,000
Eddie Jordan:
You had this great vision

1568
01:36:14,002 --> 01:36:16,536
of a megastar
in ayrton senna.

1569
01:36:18,672 --> 01:36:20,173
He was revered.

1570
01:36:20,175 --> 01:36:22,842
He was probably the most popular 
world champion

1571
01:36:22,844 --> 01:36:24,377
because he had everything,

1572
01:36:24,379 --> 01:36:26,112
and he brought great style to formula one.

1573
01:36:26,114 --> 01:36:27,847
He brought it
to another level.

1574
01:36:31,218 --> 01:36:33,853
He was one of
the most gentle people

1575
01:36:33,855 --> 01:36:35,855
that you could imagine.

1576
01:36:35,857 --> 01:36:37,357
He was getting older,

1577
01:36:37,359 --> 01:36:41,394
and he was starting
to campaign heavily for safety.

1578
01:36:41,396 --> 01:36:42,662
You've seen rubens?

1579
01:36:42,664 --> 01:36:44,030
He's all right.
He's all right.

1580
01:36:44,032 --> 01:36:47,000
He's shocked,
of course, but he's...

1581
01:36:47,002 --> 01:36:48,368
Dr. sid Watkins:
On Sunday morning,

1582
01:36:48,370 --> 01:36:51,171
just before the race,
I said to ayrton,

1583
01:36:51,173 --> 01:36:53,706
"you know, you're
the fastest guy around.

1584
01:36:53,708 --> 01:36:56,509
Why don't you quit?"

1585
01:36:56,511 --> 01:37:00,446
He said, "I can't quit.
I have to go on."

